      "text": "Some Relevant IssuesChapter - XI 360 Vigilance Manual (updated 2021) Some Relevant Issues Chapter - XI and to establish erasures or substitution of documents and restoration of obliterated writing. (3) Examination and analysis of documents available in physical form may require opinion of GEQD (Government Examiner of Questioned Documents). The following types of examination are carried out by the GEQD: - to determine the authorship of the questioned writings by a comparison (a) with known standards / accepted documents; to detect forgeries in questioned documents; (b) to determine the identity of questioned typescripts by comparison with (c) standards; to determine the identity of seal impressions; (d) to decipher erased (mechanically or chemically) or altered writings;(e) to determine whether there have been interpolations, additions, or (f) overwriting and whether there has been substitution of papers; to determine the order or sequence of writings as shown by cross strokes (g) and also to determine the sequence of strokes, creases or folds in the questioned documents where additions are suspected to have been made; to detect any tampering in wax seal impressions; (h) to decipher secret writings; (i) to determine the age of documents and other allied handwriting (j) problems. Services of the Document Division of Central Forensic ScienceLaboratory (CFSL), CBI or other forensic laboratories of Central / State Government or NABL accredited laboratories may also be used for this purpose. 11.6.1 COMPUTER FORENSICS (1) Computer forensics deals with identification, documentation, extraction and preservation of computer evidence. Typically, computer forensic tools exist in form of computer software and hardware, procedures and",
